"""

Scenario

The City of Melbourne generates large amounts of waste every month. This waste is collected from different zones and managed through public services. However, when waste collection is delayed or poorly managed, it can lead to problems like bad smells, pests, pollution, and even health issues for people living nearby. As a data analyst, I want to explore whether there is a connection between the amount of waste collected, the public complaints about waste issues, and the health and wellbeing of residents. I will use data from the citys open data portal to investigate if some zones are more affected than others and whether better waste management could improve community wellbeing.

What this Use Case will teach you

    By working on this use case, you will learn:
  • import, clean, and merge multiple real-world datasets from an API
  • to use location-based and time-based data to uncover patterns
  • to link operational data (waste collection) with social data (health and complaints)
  • to use basic data analysis and visualisation techniques to support decision-making
  • Ito identify areas that may need improved services or health interventions

Background/ Introduction

Waste management is a key part of keeping cities clean, healthy, and liveable. Poorly managed waste can lead to pollution, spread of disease, and lower quality of life. In Melbourne, different zones are responsible for collecting and managing waste. At the same time, the city collects feedback from residents through customer service complaints and regularly surveys them about their wellbeing.

    This project aims to connect the dots between:
  • How much waste is being collected,
  • Where that waste is coming from,
  • What residents are saying about waste issues,
  • And how people are feeling in terms of health and wellbeing.
"""

import requests
import pandas as pd
from io import StringIO

def API_upload(dataset_id):
    core_url = 'https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
    file_format = 'csv'
    
    web_url = f'{core_url}{dataset_id}/exports/{file_format}'
    
    params = {
        'select': '*',
        'timezone': 'UTC',
        'lang': 'en',
        'limit': '-1'
    }
    
    response = requests.get(web_url, params=params)
    
    if response.status_code == 200:
        csv_content = response.content.decode('utf-8')
        try:
            df_dataset = pd.read_csv(StringIO(csv_content), delimiter=';')
        except Exception:
            print("Semicolon delimiter failed, trying comma delimiter.")
            df_dataset = pd.read_csv(StringIO(csv_content))
        
        print(f"\nDataset: {dataset_id}\n")
        print(df_dataset.head())
        print(f"\nTotal records: {len(df_dataset)}")
        return df_dataset
    else:
        print(f"Error fetching data from {web_url}: {response.status_code}")
        return None

# Load each dataset
df_social = API_upload('social-indicators-for-city-of-melbourne-residents-2023')
df_waste = API_upload('waste-collected-per-month')
df_zones = API_upload('garbage-collection-zones')
df_complaints = API_upload('customer-service-requests-with-resolution-time')

Social Indicators Cleaning

What the code does

The cell prepares the social indicators table for analysis: it standardises column names to lowercase with underscores, drops rows missing key fields (indicator, result, respondent_group), keeps only rows where respondent_group contains Melbourne for a city-wide focus, converts result to numeric (invalid text becomes NaN), and prints a small preview to verify the changes.

Waste Dataset Cleaning

What the code does

The cell prepares the waste table for analysis. It standardises column names to lowercase_with_underscores, parses the date column to real datetimes, converts every other column (except date and month) to numeric with invalid text coerced to NaN, drops rows with missing dates, and prints a small preview.

In[3]:
# Clean column names
df_waste.columns = df_waste.columns.str.strip().str.lower().str.replace(' ', '_')

# Convert 'date' to datetime
df_waste['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_waste['date'], errors='coerce')

# Convert all numeric columns (except 'date' and 'month')
for col in df_waste.columns:
    if col not in ['date', 'month']:
        df_waste[col] = pd.to_numeric(df_waste[col], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with missing date
df_waste = df_waste.dropna(subset=['date'])

# Preview
print(df_waste[['date', 'residential', 'public_litter_bins', 'dumped_rubbish']].head())

What the results show

  • Columns are now consistent and machine-friendly; the date field is a proper datetime.
  • Waste streams such as residential, public_litter_bins, and dumped_rubbish are numeric floats, so they can be summed, averaged, resampled by month, and plotted.
  • Rows without a date were removed, preventing time-series joins from misaligning.
  • The preview confirms sensible values across streams and shows the table is ready for monthly aggregation and trend analysis.

Conclusion

This cleaning step makes df_waste analysis-ready for everything that follows: computing total_waste, building monthly_by_type, creating stacked-area composition charts, and joining with the complaints series on the date axis. As a quick sanity check before moving on, consider counting how many rows were dropped, how many NaNs were introduced by numeric coercion, and confirming units (kg or tonnes) for clear labeling. Save the cleaned table if you want fully reproducible downstream steps.

Top 10 Suburbs by Waste-Related Complaints (Bar Chart)

Why this visualisation

A bar chart is the clearest way to compare counts across categories. It ranks suburbs side-by-side so the largest complaint hotspots stand out immediately and the long tail is easy to see.

What the code does

The code counts complaints by suburb using value_counts, selects the top 10 suburbs, and draws a bar chart. It sets readable labels, rotates the x-axis names, and uses a single color so the focus stays on the size differences between bars.

In[15]:
top_suburbs = df_complaints['suburb'].value_counts().head(10)

top_suburbs.plot(kind='bar', color='orange', figsize=(10,5))
plt.title('Top 10 Suburbs by Waste-Related Complaints')
plt.xlabel('Suburb')
plt.ylabel('Number of Complaints')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

What the results show

  • Clear concentration: Melbourne has the highest complaint volume in your data window, followed by North Melbourne, Carlton, and Kensington.
  • The mid-tier includes West Melbourne and East Melbourne, with Parkville, South Yarra, Southbank, and Docklands forming a smaller tail.
  • This ranking highlights where operational effort will have the biggest impact if you are prioritizing by total volume.

Conclusion

The chart identifies the main hotspots by raw complaint counts, led by Melbourne and North Melbourne, then Carlton and Kensington. Use this list to target short-term actions such as extra crews, route checks, and QA in the top suburbs. As a next step, consider adding a rate view (complaints per 10,000 residents) and overlaying average resolution days to balance workload with service speed.

Waste Volume vs Waste-Related Complaints Over Time (Dual-axis line chart)

Why this visualisation

Two synchronized lines let us compare how complaints and waste change month by month on the same timeline. A second y-axis makes it possible to see both series clearly even though they use different units.

What the code does

It aggregates complaints per month and builds a monthly waste total by summing selected streams (residential, dumped_rubbish, public_litter_bins). The two monthly series are joined into one table and plotted together, using a secondary y-axis for waste.

In[19]:
# Complaints per month
df_complaints['month'] = df_complaints['date_received'].dt.to_period('M').dt.to_timestamp()
monthly_complaints = df_complaints.groupby('month').size()

# Waste per month (total of selected categories)
df_waste['month'] = df_waste['date'].dt.to_period('M').dt.to_timestamp()
df_waste['total_waste'] = df_waste[['residential', 'dumped_rubbish', 'public_litter_bins']].sum(axis=1)
monthly_waste = df_waste.groupby('month')['total_waste'].sum()

# Combine and plot
combined = pd.DataFrame({'complaints': monthly_complaints, 'waste': monthly_waste}).dropna()

combined.plot(figsize=(12,6), secondary_y='waste')
plt.title('Waste Volume vs Waste-Related Complaints Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

What the results show

  • Broad co-movement: months with higher waste generally line up with higher complaint counts.
  • Shared peaks appear through 20152016; dips or sharp end-drops are likely partial or quiet months.
  • Short-term spikes in waste tend to be followed by elevated complaints, hinting at a leadlag effect.

Conclusion

Complaints track waste over time, so current waste volumes are a practical early signal for next months workload. Use this chart to trigger short-term staffing and route adjustments when waste jumps. For clearer decision support, add a 3-month rolling average, annotate obvious events, and consider plotting the full total_waste (all streams) alongside the same-month and next-month complaint lines.

Monthly Total Waste vs Complaint Volume (3-month rolling)

Why this visualisation?

  • I am comparing two monthly time-series with different units (tonnes vs counts). A dual-axis line chart lets you see whether they move together or diverge.
  • Using a 3-month rolling average smooths random spikes so the underlying relationship is clearer.
  • This is ideal for an operations question: Do higher waste volumes translate to more complaints (now or with a lag)?

Datasets and columns used

  • Waste (df_waste): month (or date), total_waste (tonnes).
  • Complaints (df_complaints): date_received (or month), request_status, days_to_complete (for later metrics).
  • We first aggregate complaints to monthly citywide counts (one row per month).

Goal

Compare total waste collected (tonnes) with complaint volume (counts) over time to see whether they move together, and check if waste leads complaints by one month.

  1. Align the series: Convert the monthly waste series (monthly_total) to a dataframe, rename its time column to date, and merge with comp_city[['date','complaints']] on date a single table (aligned2) with one row per month.
  2. Order & de-dup: Ensure date is datetime, group by date to collapse any duplicates (keep first total_waste, sum complaints), then sort chronologically.
  3. Smooth: Compute 3-month rolling means: tw_roll3 (waste) and cmp_roll3 (complaints) to reduce random spikes and reveal trend.
  4. Plot: Draw tw_roll3 on the left y-axis (tonnes) and cmp_roll3 on the right y-axis (counts) against the same monthly x-axis; add labels/title/legend.
  5. Quantify same-month link: Compute Pearsons r between tw_roll3 and cmp_roll3 and annotate on the chart (your run: r = 0.81 strong positive association).
  6. Guardrail (optional): Drop the last row if its a partial month to avoid a fake end dip.
  7. Leadlag test: Shift complaints forward by one month (cmp_roll3_lag1) and correlate with current-month waste; your run: Lag-1 r = 0.81, meaning waste is a good early signal of next months complaints.
In[59]:
import pandas as pd, numpy as np, matplotlib.pyplot as plt, matplotlib.dates as mdates

# Join monthly totals with complaints
w = monthly_total.rename("total_waste").to_frame().rename_axis("date").reset_index()
c = comp_city[["date","complaints"]].copy()
w["date"] = pd.to_datetime(w["date"]); c["date"] = pd.to_datetime(c["date"])
df = (w.merge(c, on="date", how="inner")
        .groupby("date", as_index=False)
        .agg(total_waste=("total_waste","first"), complaints=("complaints","sum"))
        .sort_values("date"))
df["tw3"]  = df["total_waste"].rolling(3, 1).mean()
df["cmp3"] = df["complaints"].rolling(3, 1).mean()

# Plot
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
l1, = ax1.plot(df["date"], df["tw3"], marker="o", label="Total waste (3-mo avg)")
ax1.set_xlabel("Month"); ax1.set_ylabel("Total waste (t)")
ax1.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=2))
ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter("%Y-%m"))
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
l2, = ax2.plot(df["date"], df["cmp3"], marker="x", label="Complaints (3-mo avg)")
ax2.set_ylabel("Complaints")
ax1.legend([l1, l2], [l1.get_label(), l2.get_label()], loc="upper left")
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

# Correlations
r_same = df["tw3"].corr(df["cmp3"])
r_lag1 = df["tw3"].corr(df["cmp3"].shift(-1))  # waste vs next month's complaints
print(f"Same-month r = {r_same:.2f} | Lag-1 r = {r_lag1:.2f}")

Same-month r = 0.81 | Lag-1 r = 0.81

Waste Composition Over Time (Top Streams + Other) Stacked Area

Why this visualisation?

A stacked area chart shows both the total waste (height) and the mix of streams (colors) over time. Because there are many streams, we smooth data (3-month rolling), focus on a recent window, and plot the top 6 contributors plus other to keep it readable. This makes it easy to see which streams actually drive peaks and how the composition shifts.

Datasets & columns used

  • df_waste monthly table: time column (month or date) and stream columns: residential, commingled_recycling, mattresses, street_sweepings, public_litter_bins, dumped_rubbish, cardboard, hardwaste_to_landfill, hardwaste_recovered, hardwaste_total, green_waste.
  • We plot from a prepared matrix monthly_by_type (index = month, columns = streams).

What the code does

It cleans and sorts the monthly stream matrix, applies a 3-month rolling mean, keeps the last 60 months, selects the top 6 streams and combines the rest into other, then draws a stacked area chart with tidy date ticks. It also prints each streams share of the window and the % change in total waste across the window.

  1. Clean & sort: collapse duplicate months, sort chronologically, coerce to float, and clip negatives so stacking works.
  2. Smooth: apply a 3-month rolling mean to reduce noise and highlight the underlying pattern.
  3. Window: focus on the most recent 60 months (or all data if shorter) to avoid overplotting across many years.
  4. Top streams + other: rank streams by total tonnage over the window, keep the top 6 columns, and sum the rest into an other band.
  5. Plot & format: draw stackplot, add legend, and use monthly date locators/formatters so the x-axis labels are neat and readable.
  6. Numbers for the caption: compute each streams share of total tonnage in the window and the total % change across the window.

Risk Matrix Workload vs Speed (by suburb)

Why this visualisation?

We need to prioritise suburbs for action by looking at two things at once: workload (complaints volume) and service speed (avg resolution days). A quadrant scatter splits both metrics at their medians so the top-right quadrant (high load + slow resolution) immediately shows the highest-risk areas.

Datasets & columns used

  • comp_m (built from df_complaints by month & suburb):
    • x = complaints_per_10k (avg) if available, else avg monthly complaints (proxy).
    • y = avg_resolution_days (avg days to close per suburb).
    • total = total complaints per suburb (used for bubble sizes).

What the code does (in 23 lines)

It aggregates complaint rate and speed per suburb, computes median cut-lines, then plots a bubble scatter highlighting the top-right (high-load & slow) suburbs and annotates the most at-risk names. It also shows quadrant counts to summarise distribution.

  1. Build the risk table: From comp_m, create a per-suburb frame with x (workload), y (avg resolution days), and total (for bubble size). Fall back to avg monthly complaints if per-10k isnt available.
  2. Median split: Compute x_med and y_med to define the four quadrants.
  3. Bubble sizing & score: Scale bubbles by total. Build a simple composite score (z-scaled x+y) to rank labels inside the top-right quadrant.
  4. Select high-risk points: Flag suburbs where x x_med and y y_med as the highest-risk set.
  5. Plot: Draw a scatter for other quadrants and a highlighted scatter for high load + slow. Add dashed median lines, grid, labels, and legend.
  6. Annotate: Label the top few (e.g., 5) highest-risk suburbs by score to avoid clutter.
  7. Quadrant counts: Print the number of suburbs in each quadrant (context for how many are high-risk vs high-performing).

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

if "complaints_per_10k" in comp_m.columns:
    risk = comp_m.groupby("suburb").agg(
        x=("complaints_per_10k", "mean"),         
        y=("avg_resolution_days", "mean"),         
        total=("complaints", "sum")               
    ).dropna()
    xlabel = "Complaints per 10k (avg)"
else:
    risk = comp_m.groupby("suburb").agg(
        x=("complaints", "mean"),                  
        y=("avg_resolution_days", "mean"),
        total=("complaints", "sum")
    ).dropna()
    xlabel = "Avg monthly complaints"

x_med, y_med = risk["x"].median(), risk["y"].median()

size = 30 + 120 * (risk["total"] / (risk["total"].max() if risk["total"].max() else 1))
xz = (risk["x"] - x_med) / (risk["x"].std(ddof=0) + 1e-9)
yz = (risk["y"] - y_med) / (risk["y"].std(ddof=0) + 1e-9)
risk["score"] = xz + yz

hi = (risk["x"] >= x_med) & (risk["y"] >= y_med)

plt.figure(figsize=(7.8, 6.6))

plt.scatter(risk.loc[~hi, "x"], risk.loc[~hi, "y"],
            s=size[~hi], alpha=0.7, edgecolor="white", linewidth=0.6, label="other")

plt.scatter(risk.loc[hi, "x"],  risk.loc[hi, "y"],
            s=size[hi], alpha=0.9, edgecolor="white", linewidth=0.9, label="high load + slow")

plt.axvline(x_med, ls="--", color="#2a73cc", alpha=0.7)
plt.axhline(y_med, ls="--", color="#2a73cc", alpha=0.7)

plt.xlabel(xlabel)
plt.ylabel("Avg resolution days")

Suburb Risk Clustering What the Code Does & What We Learned

What the code does

The code groups the complaints data by suburb and computes two features for each suburb: average monthly complaints and average resolution days. It then standardises these features and runs K-Means (k = 4) to segment suburbs with similar workload (complaints) and speed (days to resolve). A silhouette score of 0.44 indicates the clusters are meaningfully separated and useful for action.

In[69]:
# Suburb risk clustering (KMeans)
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Build features from comp_m (or your per-suburb table)
X = (comp_m.groupby("suburb")
     .agg(complaints=("complaints","mean"),
          days=("avg_resolution_days","mean"))
     .dropna())

scaler = StandardScaler()
Xs = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# choose small K (34) for clear segments
k = 4
km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init="auto", random_state=0).fit(Xs)
X["cluster"] = km.labels_
print("silhouette:", round(silhouette_score(Xs, km.labels_), 3))
X.sort_values("cluster").head()

silhouette: 0.44

The clustering converts raw metrics into clear, place-based segments you can manage. Suburbs like Carlton, Kensington, and North Melbourne fall into a higher-load segment and should receive extra coverage during peak months, targeted reviews of missed bins/dumped rubbish workflow, and QA sampling. Use cluster labels in your dashboard and routing to prioritize crews, track progress by segment, and re-run monthly so suburbs can graduate from higher-risk clusters as performance improves.

import numpy as np, pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

win = monthly_by_type.sort_index().iloc[-60:] if len(monthly_by_type)>60 else monthly_by_type
F = {}
for col in win.columns:
    s = win[col].dropna()
    if len(s)<6: continue
    t = np.arange(len(s))
    slope = np.polyfit(t, s.values, 1)[0]
    yoy = (s.iloc[-12:].sum() - s.iloc[:12].sum()) if len(s)>=24 else np.nan
    mo = s.groupby(s.index.month).mean()
    seas = (mo.max()-mo.min()) if mo.notna().any() else 0
    vol = s.std()
    F[col] = [slope, yoy, seas, vol]
feat = pd.DataFrame(F, index=["slope","yoy","season","vol"]).T.dropna()

Xs = StandardScaler().fit_transform(feat)
km2 = KMeans(n_clusters=3, n_init="auto", random_state=0).fit(Xs)
feat["cluster"] = km2.labels_
feat.sort_values("cluster")

Project Conclusion & Next Steps Waste Management and Health Risks

What the data says

  • Waste and complaints rise together. When the amount of waste goes up in a month, complaints also go up, and often the following month as well.
  • Where help is needed first. The suburbs that most need attention are Melbourne, Carlton and West Melbourne because they have many complaints and take longer to resolve them.
  • What drives the totals. The biggest part of the waste is Residential. Recycling and Mattresses are also growing and add pressure.
  • When pressure is highest. Months fall into clear groups: busy months, medium months, and quiet months. A few months look unusual and should be checked for special events or disruptions.
  • Health link (in this version). We did not see a clear link between the chosen health measure and waste complaints. This may be because the data did not line up by year or there wasnt enough variation.

Recommendations

  • Plan one month ahead. If waste is high this month, get ready for more complaints next month by adding staff, routes, or hours.
  • Stabilise the hotspot suburbs. Focus extra crews and quality checks in Melbourne, Carlton and West Melbourne. Look at missed collections and dumping in those areas first.
  • Focus on the biggest streams. For Residential waste, consider larger bins or more frequent pickups in very busy streets and run simple what goes in which bin reminders. For Recycling, use quick feedback tags to cut contamination. For Mattresses, push booked kerbside pickup and store take-back.
  • Cut health risks directly. Do regular clean-ups for dumped rubbish and sharps in known spots. During hot weather, collect organic/green waste faster to limit smells and pests.

What needs to be done

  • Save simple reports for hand-off. Export: (1) monthly waste + complaints, (2) list of priority suburbs, (3) top movers by stream, (4) cluster results (months and suburbs), and (5) unusual months to review.
  • Set up a simple tracker. A one-page view that shows waste, complaints, average days to close, long delays, and the current hotspot list.
  • Add a small forecast. Use this months waste to give a next-month complaints number and a traffic-light warning (green/amber/red) so teams can prepare.
  • Turn month groups into a staffing plan. For busy months: more routes and longer hours. For quiet months: training, vehicle maintenance, and clearing backlogs.
  • Clean joins. Make sure suburb names match across tables, avoid using the last (incomplete) month for trends, and where possible use rates like complaints per 10,000 people instead of raw counts.

Enhancements

  • Line up years and use rates. Match the year of health data and complaint data, and use complaints per 10,000 people to make fair comparisons between suburbs.
  • Add context. Bring in weather (heat, rain), public holidays and big events to explain spikes and improve the forecast.
  • Map small hotspots. Use the zone shapes to pinpoint problem blocks or alleys and target clean-ups there.
  • Measure changes. When you run a campaign (e.g., contamination, mattresses), record before/after results so you know what works.
  • Make the notebook reliable. Add timeouts/retries for downloads and save a local copy so it runs even if the website is slow.

Final conclusion

The data shows a clear pattern: more waste leads to more complaints, and we can use that to plan ahead. By preparing for busy months, focusing on the three hotspot suburbs, and managing the main waste streams (especially Residential and Recycling), the city can reduce delays, prevent overflow and dumping, and lower health risks. With a small forecast, a simple tracker, and regular clean-ups in the right places, these improvements are practical and achievable.
